  "output": "This is a Python async job-scraping pipeline (~125 ATS sources в†’ SQLite dedup store), not a React app вЂ” no re-render/component-tree concerns apply. Here's what I found, adapted to what's actually here.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern вЂ” `store.py:55-74` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job, sequentially, in a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nWith ~125 sources and boards like Microsoft/Amazon/Google that page out to thousands of roles each (`max_pages=40` Г— 10/page), a single pipeline run can issue thousands of sequential round-trips to SQLite before the batched commit even happens. Classic N+1, just against a local DB instead of a web ORM вЂ” still real latency since each `execute()` has parse/plan overhead.\n\n**Fix** вЂ” bulk-fetch existing hashes in one query, diff in Python, then batch-write:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    # SQLite caps host params (~999/32766); chunk if jobs can exceed that\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i+900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?'*len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in self.conn.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif prev != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (...)\", [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(N/900) reads + 3 batched writes.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation вЂ” regex recompiled per job, `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **inside the per-job loop** (`filter_jobs` в†’ `match` is called once per job). Every job re-compiles the same keyword patterns from scratch:\n\n```python\ndef _compile(words):\n    return [re.compile(rf\"\\b{re.escape(w)}\\b\", re.IGNORECASE) for w in words if w]\n```\n\nFor thousands of jobs Г— N keywords, that's thousands of redundant `re.compile()` calls for identical patterns.\n\n**Fix** вЂ” compile once, hoist out of the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re, locations=..., cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n(`re.compile` is internally cache-backed for the *same string*, but here the pattern strings are rebuilt with `re.escape(w)` each call too, so the cache doesn't even help вЂ” it's a fresh string each time in CPython's regex cache lookup, though it will usually hit. Still, hoisting removes the per-job list-building and cache-lookup overhead entirely.)\n\n## 3. Redundant computation вЂ” `content_hash` recomputed multiple times, `models.py:66-75`, `store.py:76-97`\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a plain `@property` вЂ” it SHA-256-hashes title+location+url+department on every access. In `store.diff()`, it's accessed once for the dedup comparison, then `to_row()` (called separately in `_insert`/`_update`) recomputes it again via `asdict(self)` + `d[\"content_hash\"] = self.content_hash`. For a job with unchanged content this is 2x hashing; multiplied across thousands of jobs it's pure waste.\n\n**Fix** вЂ” cache it:\n\n```python\nfrom functools import cached_property\n\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str = field(default=\"\", repr=False, compare=False)\n```\n\n`slots=True` blocks `functools.cached_property` directly (no `__dict__`), so the practical fix is simpler: compute `content_hash` once where it's first needed (in `diff()`) and thread it through, rather than re-deriving it via a fresh `to_row()` call вЂ” e.g. pass the already-known hash into `_insert`/`_update` instead of recomputing inside `to_row()`.\n\nAlso note `to_row()` does `asdict(self)` which deep-copies the entire dataclass including nested structures before popping `raw` вЂ” for sources like Meta/Apple/Amazon that stash a `raw` dict on every `Job`, this is wasted copy work on a field that's immediately discarded. Build the row dict directly instead:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"key\": self.key, \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company,\n        \"external_id\": self.external_id, \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url,\n        \"location\": self.location, \"department\": self.department,\n        \"employment_type\": self.employment_type, \"posted_at\": self.posted_at,\n        \"salary_range\": self.salary_range, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\n## 4. Caching opportunity вЂ” no HTTP caching / conditional requests\n\nEvery scheduled run (the README mentions a 12h cron) re-fetches every board from scratch вЂ” full Greenhouse/Lever/Ashby JSON, full Google/Apple HTML pages, etc. вЂ” even though most listings are unchanged between runs. None of the fetchers (`fetchers.py`) send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`, and several APIs (Greenhouse, Ashby) support `ETag`/`Last-Modified`.\n\n**Fix** вЂ” persist `ETag`/`Last-Modified` per source in the existing `meta` table (`store.get_meta`/`set_meta` already exist for exactly this purpose) and send conditional headers, short-circuiting on `304`:\n\n```python\netag = store.get_meta(f\"etag:{company}\")\nheaders = {\"If-None-Match\": etag} if etag else {}\nr = await client.get(url, headers=headers)\nif r.status_code == 304:\n    return []  # unchanged since last run\nstore.set_meta(f\"etag:{company}\", r.headers.get(\"ETag\", \"\"))\n```\n\nThis would cut bandwidth and upstream load dramatically for the large boards (Microsoft/Amazon/Google each paginate 30-40 requests per run regardless of whether anything changed).\n\n## 5. Resource inefficiency вЂ” new TCP/TLS connection per notifier call, `notify.py:33-99`\n\n`notify_slack`, `notify_webhook`, and `notify_sms` each call the **module-level** `httpx.post(...)` / bare function, which spins up a throwaway client (new connection, new TLS handshake, no keep-alive reuse) per call. Since `dispatch()` calls these once per run, it's not costly today вЂ” but it's also blocking sync I/O (`httpx.post`, `smtplib.SMTP`) invoked from inside `pipeline.run()` which is otherwise `async` (`pipeline.py:44`). If a notifier is ever slow (Twilio/SMTP outage, retries), it stalls the whole async pipeline's event loop since nothing else yields around it.\n\n**Fix**, low priority given call volume: switch `dispatch` to run notifiers via `asyncio.to_thread` (or convert to `httpx.AsyncClient`), so a slow SMTP/Twilio call doesn't block the loop:\n\n```python\nasync def dispatch(new, changed):\n    for fn in NOTIFIERS:\n        try:\n            await asyncio.to_thread(fn, new, changed)\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {e}\")\n```\n\n## 6. Minor вЂ” regex recompiled every call in Google/hydration parsers, `fetchers.py:203-214, 391-421`\n\n`_extract_ds1` and `_apple_hydration` build fresh `re.search` patterns on every page fetched (up to `max_pages=20-40` per source). `re`'s internal compile cache absorbs most of this, but the Google `key: 'ds:1'.*?data:...` pattern uses `re.S` over potentially megabyte-sized HTML per page вЂ” compiling that pattern object once at module scope (`_DS1_RE = re.compile(...)`) rather than passing a string literal to `re.search` each call avoids the cache-lookup+recompile-on-eviction risk under memory pressure.\n\n## What's *not* a problem here\n\n- `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:1003-1024`) correctly reuses a single `httpx.AsyncClient` across all sources with a semaphore-bounded concurrency вЂ” no per-request connection churn, no leak (client is closed in `finally`).\n- `Store.diff()` already batches the `commit()` to once per run rather than per row вЂ” good instinct, just needs the same treatment applied to the reads.\n- Pagination loops (`fetch_google`, `fetch_apple`, `fetch_microsoft`, etc.) all use a `seen: set[str]` to stop on first page with no new IDs вЂ” appropriately bounds work instead of scanning to `max_pages` blindly.\n\n## Priority order\n\n1. **`store.diff()` batch fetch** вЂ” biggest real win, scales with total job count across all 125 sources.\n2. **Hoist regex compilation out of `filter_jobs`** вЂ” cheap fix, removes O(NГ—K) waste.\n3. **Conditional HTTP requests (ETag)** вЂ” cuts actual network/upstream load on a 12h cron, biggest \"infrastructure citizenship\" win.\n4. `to_row()`/`content_hash` double-compute and notifier blocking I/O are minor, worth doing opportunistically but not urgent at current scale.\n",
